<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platygastridae" genus="Pulchrisolia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchrisolia teras" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="teras">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Pulchrisolia teras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separated from all other species by the presence of deep notauli and well-defined preocellar depressions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Taken from the Greek word for monster (tέρας), in reference to the size and appearance of this formidable creature. The epithet is treated as a noun in apposition.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
